1
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:11,000
Synched and corrected by Fingersmaster.
Enjoy !

2
00:02:32,600 --> 00:02:35,728
- Did you make a wish?
- Yeah.

3
00:03:00,962 --> 00:03:03,381
No lunch. I got speech class.

4
00:03:03,506 --> 00:03:07,327
What do you need speech class for?
You talk fine.

5
00:03:07,352 --> 00:03:10,513
All right. I'll pick you up at five,
we'll ride back together.

6
00:03:10,638 --> 00:03:14,225
I can't. I got Emerging Markets
seminar at 5.30.

7
00:03:14,309 --> 00:03:18,980
Jeez, it's your birthday. Can't they
emerge without you just this once?

8
00:03:19,063 --> 00:03:21,608
- What time is my surprise party?
- What?

9
00:03:21,733 --> 00:03:23,234
Come on.

10
00:03:23,318 --> 00:03:26,237
I'm supposed to take you to drinks
and have you home at seven.

11
00:03:26,321 --> 00:03:29,324
I'll cut out early and be home at 7.15, OK?

12
00:03:29,407 --> 00:03:32,160
- All right.
- Thank you very much.

13
00:03:56,100 --> 00:03:58,812
- Morning, Tess.
- Morning.

14
00:04:00,438 --> 00:04:02,565
- Hi, Tess.
- Hi.

15
00:04:11,407 --> 00:04:13,701
Mr Turkel's line.

16
00:04:15,078 --> 00:04:17,163
Who's calling, please?

17
00:04:18,706 --> 00:04:20,542
Hold on a moment.

18
00:04:20,625 --> 00:04:22,669
Mr Lutz?

19
00:04:25,755 --> 00:04:28,341
Hold on a second, all right?

20
00:04:35,723 --> 00:04:37,809
Mr Turkel?

21
00:04:40,812 --> 00:04:44,023
Mr Alagash... Hi.

22
00:04:44,107 --> 00:04:48,778
- Mr Alagash is real anxious to talk to you.
- You couldn't maybe get him to hold?

23
00:04:48,862 --> 00:04:51,573
You got him in Dentitech -
the one I said go short on.

24
00:04:51,656 --> 00:04:54,534
It's fine, but he don't wanna
hear it from a secretary.

25
00:04:54,617 --> 00:04:57,704
- There's no paper.
- What?

26
00:04:57,787 --> 00:05:02,500
There is no goddamned paper
in this stall. Get me some?

27
00:05:09,799 --> 00:05:13,219
Thanks. You're very kind.

28
00:05:20,935 --> 00:05:24,856
You're short on Dentitech at 18.
He'll be right here.

29
00:05:41,122 --> 00:05:46,294
See Dentitech closing? 17 and 1/8. Come Monday,
I bet it's 16 and still sittin' there.

30
00:05:46,419 --> 00:05:50,507
- How you figure?
- They went public at 23 with one product.

31
00:05:50,590 --> 00:05:52,926
Plaque-removing mouthwash?

32
00:05:53,009 --> 00:05:56,221
You rinse, you get this glob of plaque
you gotta spit out.

33
00:05:56,304 --> 00:05:58,973
Maybe it'll be big, but no one ever got rich

34
00:05:59,057 --> 00:06:03,228
overestimating what
the American public wants to taste.

35
00:06:03,311 --> 00:06:05,188
Maybe.

36
00:06:06,314 --> 00:06:10,944
Before I run, Tess, I have some
good news and some bad news.

37
00:06:11,611 --> 00:06:17,325
The straight shot is they turned you down
for the entrée programme again.

38
00:06:17,408 --> 00:06:19,702
- Why?
- We did all we could, Tessy.

39
00:06:19,828 --> 00:06:22,831
You've got to remember you're up against
Harvard and Wharton graduates.

40
00:06:22,956 --> 00:06:26,668
You've got some night school,
some secretarial time on your sheet.

41
00:06:26,751 --> 00:06:29,921
- Christians and lions, Tess.
- That's right.

42
00:06:30,046 --> 00:06:33,174
- And the good news?
- Dave has a friend.

43
00:06:33,299 --> 00:06:38,555
Bob in Arbitrage. You're so hungry,
they're looking for hungry down there.

44
00:06:38,638 --> 00:06:41,933
- Really?
- Hungry's the name of the game down there.

45
00:06:42,016 --> 00:06:45,603
Bob's looking for a new assistant
and wants to meet you for a drink.

46
00:06:45,687 --> 00:06:48,439
This isn't another setup?

47
00:06:50,066 --> 00:06:52,777
Do I look like a pimp?

48
00:06:56,990 --> 00:07:02,036
Bob says he's looking for hungry,
I think to myself "Tess". The rest is up to you.

49
00:07:02,120 --> 00:07:05,123
- Bob in Arbitrage.
- Bob Speck.

50
00:07:05,206 --> 00:07:08,168
Extension 256. Expecting your call.

51
00:07:08,251 --> 00:07:10,420
Go get 'em, Tessy.

52
00:07:14,382 --> 00:07:17,385
You should have told us.
Congratulations, Tessy.

53
00:07:26,686 --> 00:07:27,812
Thanks.

54
00:07:37,989 --> 00:07:40,074
Mick?

55
00:07:56,758 --> 00:07:58,843
Surprise.

56
00:08:00,720 --> 00:08:03,389
Happy birthday.

57
00:08:14,150 --> 00:08:16,611
You look great.

58
00:08:26,538 --> 00:08:28,915
Come here.

59
00:08:30,166 --> 00:08:35,088
You know, Mick, just once I could go for,
like, a sweater or some earrings.

60
00:08:35,171 --> 00:08:40,176
You know? A present that I can
actually wear outside of this apartment.

61
00:08:52,063 --> 00:08:53,773
So...

62
00:08:54,858 --> 00:08:57,402
Is this where you usually meet for drinks?

63
00:08:57,485 --> 00:09:01,448
This is a big week.
A super week. We are celebrating.

64
00:09:01,531 --> 00:09:05,660
So, Arbitrage. Talk about adrenaline, huh?

65
00:09:05,743 --> 00:09:09,622
What do you think is the most
important quality for a great arbitrager?

66
00:09:09,706 --> 00:09:13,668
- Well, we'll go through all that at the hotel.
- The hotel?

67
00:09:13,751 --> 00:09:16,253
The company keeps a suite
at the Ritz Carlton.

68
00:09:16,254 --> 00:09:19,340
When it's empty they give it
to us boys on a bonus basis.

69
00:09:19,424 --> 00:09:21,843
We're gonna party.

70
00:09:21,926 --> 00:09:24,596
I'm sorry. Allow me. I'm so sorry.

71
00:09:24,679 --> 00:09:28,850
- Hey, Bob. Please.
- Sorry, I just... I get a little carried away.

72
00:09:30,101 --> 00:09:35,231
You know what? Arbitrage has put out this sort of
"Introduction to..." tape for the business schools.

73
00:09:35,315 --> 00:09:40,153
- Why don't we put it in. If you have any questions...
- That would be great. Thanks.

74
00:09:50,955 --> 00:09:53,500
It's the wrong tape. Unless of course you...

75
00:09:53,583 --> 00:09:57,420
Bob, you're not seriously looking
for a new assistant, are you?

76
00:09:57,504 --> 00:10:01,090
Not exactly at this moment. But I'm always
on the lookout for new blood.

77
00:10:01,174 --> 00:10:03,426
I am hungry, Bob, but I am not that hungry.

78
00:10:03,510 --> 00:10:05,637
- I wouldn't put it that way.
- I would.

79
00:10:05,720 --> 00:10:10,308
- Would you just pull over right here, please?
- What are you doing?

80
00:10:12,811 --> 00:10:15,438
Party, Bob.

81
00:10:43,133 --> 00:10:45,218
Hello, Tess.

82
00:10:47,887 --> 00:10:50,348
You're late, Tess.

83
00:11:10,201 --> 00:11:12,287
Yo, David.

84
00:11:19,461 --> 00:11:20,628
Little bitch.

85
00:11:20,712 --> 00:11:23,173
You gotta see this to believe it.

86
00:11:24,257 --> 00:11:25,842
Take it easy.

87
00:11:25,925 --> 00:11:27,802
Bastard.

88
00:11:28,970 --> 00:11:32,765
- Tess... Tess... Tess...
- I know.

89
00:11:32,849 --> 00:11:36,978
You don't get ahead in this world
by calling your boss a pimp.

90
00:11:37,061 --> 00:11:39,439
Well, he is.

91
00:11:39,522 --> 00:11:41,627
Been lookin' at your file here.

92
00:11:41,728 --> 00:11:45,028
This is the third time in six months
I've had to place you.

93
00:11:45,111 --> 00:11:48,823
- It wasn't my fault.
- Where have I heard that before?

94
00:11:48,948 --> 00:11:51,034
Ruth, look it.
I'm 30 years old.

95
00:11:51,117 --> 00:11:54,913
It took me five years of night school,
but I got my degree with honours.

96
00:11:55,038 --> 00:11:57,123
I know I could do a job.

97
00:11:57,207 --> 00:12:01,920
Ask any of my bosses, even Lutz,
if Tess McGill hasn't called a few.

98
00:12:02,045 --> 00:12:06,341
You ask 'em. I don't think
they're gonna sing your praises, Tess.

99
00:12:11,012 --> 00:12:15,558
Here's something for you.
Transferring down from Boston.

100
00:12:15,642 --> 00:12:21,147
Mergers and Acquisitions.
Name is Parker. Starts Monday.

101
00:12:21,231 --> 00:12:23,566
- You go home and cool off.
- OK.

102
00:12:23,650 --> 00:12:25,985
Tess...

103
00:12:26,069 --> 00:12:31,366
This is the last time I can help you.
Four strikes, you're out.

104
00:12:37,580 --> 00:12:43,253
- Tess McGill for Katharine Parker's office.
- It's the last desk. At the end of the aisle.

105
00:13:39,309 --> 00:13:42,437
Hi. I'm Katharine Parker. You must be Tess.

106
00:13:42,520 --> 00:13:44,355
Hi.

107
00:13:45,231 --> 00:13:47,484
Great bunny.

108
00:13:48,276 --> 00:13:53,323
I don't usually have a bunny on my desk.
It was my birthday a few days ago.

109
00:13:53,406 --> 00:13:56,993
- No kidding. Mine's next Tuesday. How old?
- 30.

110
00:13:57,076 --> 00:14:01,289
Really? Well, I'll be 30 next Tuesday.
We're practically twins.

111
00:14:02,123 --> 00:14:05,293
- Except I'm older.
- Just barely.

112
00:14:05,418 --> 00:14:10,965
I've never worked for somebody who was
younger than me before. Or for a woman.

113
00:14:11,049 --> 00:14:15,678
Well, there's a first time for everything.
It's not going to be a problem, is it, Tess?

114
00:14:15,762 --> 00:14:17,972
- No.
- Good.

115
00:14:18,056 --> 00:14:23,728
Why don't you pour us a couple of coffees
and come on inside? I'm light, no sugar.

116
00:14:28,817 --> 00:14:31,528
The stock is at 38, the tender's at 56.

117
00:14:32,278 --> 00:14:34,364
Come in.

118
00:14:34,447 --> 00:14:36,658
Yeah, what do we do about that?

119
00:14:36,741 --> 00:14:40,161
Well, I just checked my three.
What are yours?

120
00:14:41,204 --> 00:14:43,706
Yeah, I have that one.

121
00:14:43,790 --> 00:14:46,459
I think he's in an underwater position.

122
00:14:46,543 --> 00:14:50,797
All right. That's our first and second call,
and then we'll see where we are.

123
00:14:50,880 --> 00:14:53,967
I'll count the minutes. Bye.

124
00:14:54,092 --> 00:14:55,969
Thanks.

125
00:14:57,178 --> 00:14:59,806
So, Tess, a few ground rules.

126
00:14:59,889 --> 00:15:03,101
The way I look at it,
you are my link with the outside world.

127
00:15:03,184 --> 00:15:05,645
People's impression of me starts with you.

128
00:15:05,728 --> 00:15:09,315
You're tough when it's warranted,
accommodating when you can be.

129
00:15:09,399 --> 00:15:13,153
You're accurate. You're punctual.
You never make a promise you can't keep.

130
00:15:13,236 --> 00:15:16,156
I'm never on another line, I'm in a meeting.

131
00:15:16,239 --> 00:15:19,701
I consider us a team, Tess,
and as such we have a uniform.

132
00:15:19,784 --> 00:15:22,078
Simple, elegant, impeccable.

133
00:15:22,162 --> 00:15:26,916
"Dress shabbily, they notice the dress.
Dress impeccably, they notice the woman."

134
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:29,085
Coco Chanel.

135
00:15:30,670 --> 00:15:33,631
How do I look?

136
00:15:33,715 --> 00:15:38,136
You look terrific.
You might wanna rethink the jewellery.

137
00:15:40,221 --> 00:15:45,185
I want your input, Tess. I welcome your ideas
and I like to see hard work rewarded.

138
00:15:45,268 --> 00:15:49,606
It's a two-way street on my team.
Am I making myself clear?

139
00:15:49,689 --> 00:15:52,066
Yes, Katharine.

140
00:15:54,527 --> 00:15:57,363
- And call me Katharine.
- OK.

141
00:15:58,323 --> 00:16:01,117
So, let's get to work, shall we?

142
00:16:01,201 --> 00:16:07,373
This department's profile last year was damn pitiful.
Our team's got its work cut out for it.

143
00:16:08,166 --> 00:16:10,251
OK. Thanks.

144
00:16:11,961 --> 00:16:16,508
Damn. I forgot my pills again.
It's the third time this month.

145
00:16:16,591 --> 00:16:19,135
Did you hear about that shot
they got in Europe?

146
00:16:19,219 --> 00:16:23,556
They're giving it to women, in their arm.
It's good for five years.

147
00:16:23,640 --> 00:16:25,850
Damn pills. I'm always forgetting 'em.

148
00:16:28,978 --> 00:16:31,898
- I thought you might like this.
- Thank you.

149
00:16:34,734 --> 00:16:37,654
Tess, would you come in here, please,
and bring a notebook?

150
00:16:37,987 --> 00:16:40,532
They've sold the paper and printing divisions.

151
00:16:40,615 --> 00:16:44,702
They sell Distribution too,
we're talking real scorched earth.

152
00:16:44,786 --> 00:16:46,996
Come on in.

153
00:16:47,080 --> 00:16:50,333
Tess, this is Ginny. Ginny, Tess.

154
00:16:51,167 --> 00:16:55,421
Being new in town, I thought I'd throw a little
cocktail thing to introduce myself to the department.

155
00:16:55,505 --> 00:16:59,801
Ginny here has some great ideas.
Will you jot them down?

156
00:16:59,884 --> 00:17:03,888
The caterer is called Acme Eats.
You can get the number from Information.

157
00:17:03,972 --> 00:17:06,266
They do the usual hors d'oeuvres and such.

158
00:17:06,349 --> 00:17:09,853
The Raging Bull has a bartender service.

159
00:17:09,936 --> 00:17:13,231
And the liquor store
on Broadway and Liberty delivers.

160
00:17:13,314 --> 00:17:16,568
- Got that, Bess?
- Tess, yeah.

161
00:17:16,651 --> 00:17:21,114
- If that's the way that you wanna go.
- You have another idea?

162
00:17:21,197 --> 00:17:25,827
Well, I was just reading in W about dim sum -
these little Chinese dumplings.

163
00:17:25,952 --> 00:17:29,539
A restaurant on Mott Street
does them for cocktail parties.

164
00:17:29,622 --> 00:17:33,626
- I love those little dumplings.
- It might be more fun than the usual tidbits.

165
00:17:33,710 --> 00:17:37,714
- I have it on my desk. I could get it.
- You read W?

166
00:17:37,797 --> 00:17:42,927
I read a lot of things. You never know
where the big ideas could come from.

167
00:17:43,052 --> 00:17:47,640
I guess you're right. If dumplings
can be considered a big idea.

168
00:17:47,724 --> 00:17:52,145
- Well, that oughta get you started...
- Ginny, thank you so much.

169
00:17:52,228 --> 00:17:54,773
- Back to the gold mines.
- Right.

170
00:17:54,856 --> 00:17:56,983
- You'll set those up?
- Right away.

171
00:17:57,066 --> 00:18:00,403
Dim sum, Tess. I like it, contribution-wise.

172
00:18:00,487 --> 00:18:02,739
Keep it up.

173
00:18:05,742 --> 00:18:09,204
The chief says "We will respect your wish.
We will give you an honourable death."

174
00:18:09,287 --> 00:18:11,372
"But first, keke."

175
00:18:12,457 --> 00:18:15,126
Excuse me. Excuse me.

176
00:18:16,377 --> 00:18:18,755
- Dim sum?
- Yes, yes.

177
00:18:24,594 --> 00:18:27,514
Come on, Katharine. What do you say?

178
00:18:27,597 --> 00:18:32,268
Jim, the man who spends
every weekend in August glued to his desk,

179
00:18:32,352 --> 00:18:35,772
that man knows that I can't
just sneak out of my own party.

180
00:18:36,397 --> 00:18:41,486
I'll tell you what, though. You get me
in on the Southeast Air divestiture plan,

181
00:18:41,569 --> 00:18:45,824
I'll buy you a drink.
Bottle of Cristal, two straws.

182
00:18:47,033 --> 00:18:50,161
- Deal?
- Okey-dokey.

183
00:18:51,079 --> 00:18:53,289
- Dim sum?
- Hi.

184
00:18:54,124 --> 00:18:56,334
Thank you. What a slob.

185
00:18:56,417 --> 00:18:59,045
You were so smooth with him.
I probably would have...

186
00:18:59,129 --> 00:19:04,050
Never burn bridges. Today's junior prick,
tomorrow's senior partner.

187
00:19:04,134 --> 00:19:08,179
- So, how do you think the party's going?
- Pretty well, I think.

188
00:19:08,263 --> 00:19:11,182
Should I stop serving now?

189
00:19:11,266 --> 00:19:13,726
- Better make one more round.
- Right.

190
00:19:13,852 --> 00:19:17,814
I'd love to help you, but we can't busy
the quarterback with passing out the Gatorade.

191
00:19:17,897 --> 00:19:20,316
Arnie, my hero. You've come.

192
00:19:33,746 --> 00:19:35,582
Yeah?

193
00:19:38,585 --> 00:19:41,171
I have an idea
and you said I could come to you.

194
00:19:41,296 --> 00:19:43,381
Shoot.

195
00:19:46,301 --> 00:19:51,097
Well, you know how Trask Industries
has been looking to buy into broadcasting?

196
00:19:51,181 --> 00:19:53,808
- Something about that the department is...
- Working on it, yeah.

197
00:19:53,892 --> 00:19:58,730
I've been following it myself,
and all of a sudden I thought "radio".

198
00:19:58,813 --> 00:20:03,151
- Trask is looking for television stations.
- So is every Tom, Dick and Harry.

199
00:20:03,234 --> 00:20:06,863
My idea is that they get their feet wet in radio
and build from there.

200
00:20:06,946 --> 00:20:09,657
It's not as glamorous
as jumping right into TV,

201
00:20:09,741 --> 00:20:13,661
but it's a solid place to start
and there's a lot more of them for sale.

202
00:20:13,787 --> 00:20:18,166
Plus it would solve Trask's problem with
the Japanese competitors trying to take him over,

203
00:20:18,249 --> 00:20:22,128
because FCC forbids foreign ownership
of radio as well as TV.

204
00:20:26,049 --> 00:20:31,471
Interesting. You've been
following this, you say?

205
00:20:31,554 --> 00:20:33,223
Yeah.

206
00:20:33,348 --> 00:20:37,560
No chance you overheard it,
say on the elevator?

207
00:20:38,144 --> 00:20:41,356
- No, no way.
- Somewhere.

208
00:20:41,481 --> 00:20:43,650
It's my idea.

209
00:20:43,733 --> 00:20:46,277
Good, good.

210
00:20:47,987 --> 00:20:53,910
- Discuss it with anyone else?
- Nope. You think there's something there?

211
00:20:53,993 --> 00:20:56,041
Well, I can think it through for you.

212
00:20:56,142 --> 00:20:58,289
Why don't you leave me your notes?
I'll have a look-see.

213
00:20:58,373 --> 00:21:00,416
OK.

214
00:21:00,500 --> 00:21:04,629
I've been trying to get into the entrée
programme and this would be a big push.

215
00:21:04,712 --> 00:21:08,424
- If anything happens, you'll...
- Absolutely, Tess.

216
00:21:08,508 --> 00:21:11,261
Two-way street, remember?

217
00:21:11,344 --> 00:21:13,429
Yeah, thank you.

218
00:21:34,075 --> 00:21:38,955
It's just... It's so exciting.
I mean, she takes me seriously.

219
00:21:39,038 --> 00:21:44,210
I know you hate when I say this,
but I think it's because she's a woman.

220
00:21:44,294 --> 00:21:47,380
There's none of that
chasing-around-the-desk crap.

221
00:21:47,464 --> 00:21:51,718
And it's like she wants to be my mentor,
which is exactly what I needed.

222
00:21:51,801 --> 00:21:54,429
I feel like I'm finally gettin' somewhere.

223
00:21:54,512 --> 00:21:59,350
That's great, but let's step on it
or the pizza's gonna freeze, honey.

224
00:21:59,434 --> 00:22:04,481
Maybe we could all go out sometime.
Dinner in the city.

225
00:22:04,564 --> 00:22:07,108
You would like her, I think.

226
00:22:07,692 --> 00:22:10,653
God. Remember when all you had to do
was a few buckles?

227
00:22:10,737 --> 00:22:13,406
Yeah. Those were the days.

228
00:22:13,490 --> 00:22:18,745
I called the inn. All they can give you
is a ground-floor single in the new wing.

229
00:22:19,913 --> 00:22:22,457
Did you tell them it was me?

230
00:22:22,540 --> 00:22:24,793
Well, I said Parker.

231
00:23:03,123 --> 00:23:08,586
It's this tower room with a canopy bed
and a fireplace big enough to stand in.

232
00:23:08,670 --> 00:23:12,423
Perfect. Everything's in place.

233
00:23:13,216 --> 00:23:17,679
- For what?
- The man I've been seeing for a while.

234
00:23:17,762 --> 00:23:22,600
I think he's it. And I think
this could be the weekend we decide.

235
00:23:22,684 --> 00:23:26,938
He said there was something very important
he wanted to discuss with me.

236
00:23:27,021 --> 00:23:29,107
I think he's gonna pop the question.

237
00:23:29,190 --> 00:23:31,067
- You do?
- I think so.

238
00:23:31,151 --> 00:23:35,488
We're in the same city now.
I've indicated that I'm receptive to an offer.

239
00:23:35,613 --> 00:23:39,367
I've cleared the month of June.
And I am, after all, me.

240
00:23:41,327 --> 00:23:43,830
What if he doesn't pop the question?

241
00:23:45,957 --> 00:23:48,710
I really don't think that's a variable.

242
00:23:48,835 --> 00:23:54,799
Tess, you don't get anywhere in this world
by waiting for what you want to come to you.

243
00:23:54,924 --> 00:23:57,677
You make it happen.

244
00:23:57,760 --> 00:24:01,055
Watch me, Tess. Learn from me.

245
00:24:03,808 --> 00:24:08,062
By the way, I ran your Trask radio idea
by some of our people.

246
00:24:08,480 --> 00:24:12,066
It seems Trask is dead set on television.

247
00:24:12,150 --> 00:24:15,695
But it wasn't out in left field either.
I really liked the idea.

248
00:24:15,779 --> 00:24:20,992
You just keep plugging and bring me
your ideas, and we'll see what we can do.

249
00:24:21,659 --> 00:24:24,245
- Thank you, Katharine.
- Tess...

250
00:24:27,040 --> 00:24:29,667
Look at me. Who makes it happen?

251
00:24:32,170 --> 00:24:34,380
I do.

252
00:24:34,464 --> 00:24:37,300
Who does?

253
00:24:37,383 --> 00:24:39,677
I do. I make it happen.

254
00:24:39,886 --> 00:24:43,640
That's right. Only then
do we get what we deserve.

255
00:25:08,915 --> 00:25:11,126
Miss Parker's office.

256
00:25:11,209 --> 00:25:13,211
Hi, Katharine.

257
00:25:13,336 --> 00:25:16,256
- You what?
- Broke it. Skiing.

258
00:25:16,381 --> 00:25:21,553
They won't be able to move me for two weeks,
so this is what I need you to do.

259
00:25:21,636 --> 00:25:23,930
Water plants. OK.

260
00:25:25,223 --> 00:25:27,475
Cable comes on Friday.

261
00:25:27,600 --> 00:25:29,978
Easy with the leg, will you?

262
00:25:30,061 --> 00:25:32,272
Quit staring up my gown.

263
00:25:32,355 --> 00:25:37,110
Now, I'm staying at my parents' house
and the housekeeper is in Barbados.

264
00:25:37,193 --> 00:25:40,947
What a mess. You need to let in
the flower man and the cleaning lady.

265
00:25:41,030 --> 00:25:45,160
Sort through the mail.
The entrance code for the front door is...

266
00:25:46,327 --> 00:25:49,998
It's 754-3-2000.

267
00:25:50,748 --> 00:25:52,876
I know there's more, but I can't think of what.

268
00:25:53,042 --> 00:25:57,964
Go through the calendar on my desk.
There's a bunch of invitations to be RSVP'd.

269
00:25:58,047 --> 00:26:03,094
I know I'm asking an awful lot, Tess,
but I don't know what else to do.

270
00:26:03,219 --> 00:26:07,056
- I need you to take over.
- OK. Bye.

271
00:27:25,677 --> 00:27:29,305
Regarding those horrid little
knick-knacks from the Alberts...

272
00:27:29,389 --> 00:27:33,268
Dear Eleanor and Gary.
Thank you for the salt and pepper shakers.

273
00:27:33,351 --> 00:27:39,399
Not only are they the perfect house-warming
gift, but it was so dear of you to think of me.

274
00:27:40,650 --> 00:27:45,655
Dear Sister. It's hard to believe it's been eight
years since we said goodbye to Wellesley,

275
00:27:45,738 --> 00:27:48,575
but of course we never really say goodbye.

276
00:27:48,658 --> 00:27:52,912
On behalf of the Alumni Giving Fund,
I am writing to you to ask...

277
00:27:58,084 --> 00:28:03,590
Dear Sister. It's hard to believe it's been eight
years since we said goodbye to Wellesley,

278
00:28:03,673 --> 00:28:06,342
but of course we never really say goodbye.

279
00:28:06,384 --> 00:28:10,680
On behalf of the Alumni Giving Fund,
I am writing to you to ask...

280
00:28:14,100 --> 00:28:17,353
To ask... To a... To ask... To... ask...

281
00:28:18,688 --> 00:28:21,441
I am writing to you to ask...

282
00:28:22,650 --> 00:28:24,778
Dear Momo and Baa.

283
00:28:24,861 --> 00:28:27,280
Here I am living in Mummy's house

284
00:28:27,363 --> 00:28:31,493
while I brave the New York real-estate market
looking for a place of my own.

285
00:28:31,576 --> 00:28:36,915
I miss you all terribly, but it will be so lovely
to see you when you return from Barbados.

286
00:28:36,998 --> 00:28:40,919
Till then, have fun. Much love to you
and, of course, to Claudette.

287
00:28:41,002 --> 00:28:43,129
Love, Kiki.

288
00:28:45,006 --> 00:28:47,884
To Jack Trainer,
Dewey Stone & Company, from me.

289
00:28:47,967 --> 00:28:51,387
Re: Trask Industries -
radio network acquisition.

290
00:28:51,471 --> 00:28:56,518
Hard copy on this from the home
computer. Do not go through Tess.

291
00:29:00,605 --> 00:29:03,358
To Jack Trainer,
Dewey Stone & Company, from me.

292
00:29:03,483 --> 00:29:07,070
Re: Trask Industries -
radio network acquisition.

293
00:29:07,153 --> 00:29:11,449
Hard copy on this from the home
computer. Do not go through Tess.

294
00:29:29,175 --> 00:29:31,386
"Two-way street."

295
00:29:32,303 --> 00:29:34,472
And "You make it happen".

296
00:30:16,347 --> 00:30:19,517
- What? No class?
- No class.

297
00:30:21,060 --> 00:30:23,605
Tess, this is not what it looks like.

298
00:30:23,730 --> 00:30:26,816
I mean, it is what it looks like,
but I can explain.

299
00:30:26,941 --> 00:30:30,737
- Well, not exactly explain.
- You snake.

300
00:30:33,239 --> 00:30:34,282
Shit.

301
00:30:41,873 --> 00:30:44,793
Come on, Tess. I'm sorry, I really am.

302
00:30:45,627 --> 00:30:48,379
I love you. Come on.

303
00:30:48,463 --> 00:30:51,216
Come back and hit me.

304
00:30:51,382 --> 00:30:52,884
Please.

305
00:31:37,971 --> 00:31:40,932
Hello. Mr Trainer's office, please?

306
00:31:42,434 --> 00:31:46,563
Hello. Tess McGill calling from Petty Marsh.
May I put her through?

307
00:31:46,646 --> 00:31:48,731
Thank you.

308
00:31:51,860 --> 00:31:53,820
Mr Trainer?

309
00:31:53,903 --> 00:31:59,742
Hi, this is Tess McGill. I work with Katharine
Parker over here in Mergers and Acquisitions.

310
00:31:59,826 --> 00:32:03,580
I have a proposal that
I'd like to discuss with you.

311
00:32:03,705 --> 00:32:06,249
Not over the phone, though.

312
00:32:07,208 --> 00:32:10,545
I have an opening
tomorrow morning at 10 o'clock.

313
00:32:11,588 --> 00:32:13,465
OK.

314
00:32:13,548 --> 00:32:17,385
I'll messenger an outline
over to you right now.

315
00:32:17,469 --> 00:32:19,429
Bye.

316
00:32:38,865 --> 00:32:42,994
Yes, I'm calling for Katharine Parker
in regard to your invitation.

317
00:32:43,077 --> 00:32:47,499
Miss Parker is out of town, but Miss Tess
McGill will be attending in her place.

318
00:32:47,582 --> 00:32:49,042
Yes. Thank you.

319
00:33:01,971 --> 00:33:04,516
Why does it do that?

320
00:33:04,599 --> 00:33:08,103
- For cleaning.
- Are you kiddin' me?

321
00:33:08,186 --> 00:33:10,271
No.

322
00:33:14,484 --> 00:33:16,945
What is this thing you're going to anyway?

323
00:33:17,070 --> 00:33:21,324
The closing party for the Minidyne-Dalton
merger. Dewey Stone is throwing it.

324
00:33:21,407 --> 00:33:24,661
That's where Trainer works.
It's the perfect time to meet him.

325
00:33:24,744 --> 00:33:28,540
Mix business with pleasure.
Fringe times are crucial.

326
00:33:28,623 --> 00:33:31,084
What'd you do, snatch her invite?

327
00:33:31,209 --> 00:33:33,294
Well, she can't use it.

328
00:33:33,378 --> 00:33:37,799
It's important for me to start interacting
with people, not as a secretary...

329
00:33:37,882 --> 00:33:40,552
But as a total impostor. Right.

330
00:33:43,680 --> 00:33:46,182
This is it.

331
00:33:47,684 --> 00:33:51,104
It needs some bows or somethin'.

332
00:33:51,187 --> 00:33:55,483
No. It's simple, elegant,
yet makes a statement.

333
00:33:55,567 --> 00:34:00,280
Says to people: confident, a risk-taker,
not afraid to be noticed.

334
00:34:00,363 --> 00:34:05,034
Then you hit 'em with your smarts.
Here. Shoes. I need shoes.

335
00:34:07,245 --> 00:34:10,540
$6,000? It's not even leather.

336
00:34:12,834 --> 00:34:14,878
$6,000?

337
00:34:17,672 --> 00:34:20,300
$6,000.

338
00:34:20,383 --> 00:34:25,013
- Cyn, I can't breathe so good.
- Oh, God. Come here.

339
00:34:25,138 --> 00:34:29,058
Sit down. Let's see
if she's got anything soothing.

340
00:34:42,405 --> 00:34:46,451
Valium. In the convenient economy size.

341
00:34:46,618 --> 00:34:49,078
- You sure?
- Just chills you ever so slightly.

342
00:34:49,162 --> 00:34:51,623
You won't even notice it.

343
00:34:57,128 --> 00:35:00,048
Are you sure about this?

344
00:35:00,131 --> 00:35:04,093
You wanna be taken seriously,
you need serious hair.

345
00:35:39,003 --> 00:35:41,933
Go for the jugular. Look, I've been
telling you this for thre weeks.

346
00:35:41,934 --> 00:35:43,716
There are 19 million shares outstanding.

347
00:35:43,800 --> 00:35:47,303
We got 25%. We get another 5%,
we've got 'em by the throat.

348
00:35:47,387 --> 00:35:50,140
- Trainer, let's grab 'em by the balls.
- Leave our hearts at home.

349
00:35:50,223 --> 00:35:55,770
Cut 'em off at the knees. They'll be
eating out of our hands. What do you say?

350
00:35:55,895 --> 00:35:59,065
- Anybody thirsty?
- We need this one, Trainer.

351
00:35:59,149 --> 00:36:02,277
- You need this one.
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.

352
00:36:15,123 --> 00:36:19,210
- I've been looking for you.
- Why? Do you know me?

353
00:36:19,335 --> 00:36:24,382
No, but I promised myself that,
when I saw you, I would get to know you.

354
00:36:25,133 --> 00:36:28,219
You're the first woman I've seen in one of
these damn things that dresses like a woman,

355
00:36:28,344 --> 00:36:32,056
not like a woman thinks
a man would dress if he was a woman.

356
00:36:32,140 --> 00:36:35,894
- Thank you, I guess.
- What are you doing here?

357
00:36:35,977 --> 00:36:40,440
I'm looking for someone myself. His name
is Jack Trainer. He works at Dewey Stone.

358
00:36:40,523 --> 00:36:43,151
Do you know if he's here?

359
00:36:43,234 --> 00:36:45,528
Why are you looking for him?

360
00:36:45,653 --> 00:36:48,072
Well, because I have a meeting with him tomorrow.

361
00:36:48,156 --> 00:36:52,368
I thought it might be nice
to say hello and get a head start.

362
00:36:53,495 --> 00:36:57,040
Well, he just left.

363
00:37:02,045 --> 00:37:05,507
- I should be going myself.
- Have a drink with me.

364
00:37:05,590 --> 00:37:08,718
I can't. What's your name?

365
00:37:08,802 --> 00:37:11,971
No. No names. No business cards.

366
00:37:12,055 --> 00:37:14,516
- No "You must know so and so".
- What is this?

367
00:37:14,599 --> 00:37:18,478
No résumés. Let's just meet
like human beings for once.

368
00:37:21,022 --> 00:37:24,651
It's nice to meet you, whatever your name is,
but I really do have to go.

369
00:37:24,984 --> 00:37:28,154
Please. Please. One drink.

370
00:37:31,032 --> 00:37:34,160
OK, one drink. But I'm buying.

371
00:37:34,244 --> 00:37:36,329
OK, but it's an open bar.

372
00:37:36,412 --> 00:37:39,415
I knew that. I meant that
if it wasn't, I would be buying.

373
00:37:39,499 --> 00:37:40,959
Yeah.

374
00:37:41,042 --> 00:37:44,796
- Tequila Gold. Doubles.
- Tequila?

375
00:37:45,088 --> 00:37:49,551
Yeah. I promised myself that
when we met we'd drink tequila.

376
00:37:49,634 --> 00:37:53,221
No Chardonnay, no frog water.

377
00:37:53,304 --> 00:37:55,598
Real drinks.

378
00:38:08,736 --> 00:38:11,739
These things are usually so boring.

379
00:38:15,034 --> 00:38:17,120
I wouldn't know.

380
00:38:18,705 --> 00:38:21,499
Power to the people.

381
00:38:21,583 --> 00:38:23,918
The little people.

382
00:38:29,132 --> 00:38:32,760
Oh boy, oh boy, oh boy, oh boy.

383
00:38:32,844 --> 00:38:35,472
Oh boy, oh boy...

384
00:38:35,555 --> 00:38:38,850
- You OK?
- I'm fine. I'm just fine.

385
00:38:38,933 --> 00:38:46,316
I took an antihistamine before,
and it just makes for a nice little buzz.

386
00:38:47,942 --> 00:38:52,113
I didn't know they let
bad girls into these things.

387
00:38:52,197 --> 00:38:55,450
- Do I look like I don't belong here?
- No.

388
00:38:55,533 --> 00:39:01,790
No, no. I'm sure you're a real ace
at whatever it is that you do do.

389
00:39:01,873 --> 00:39:06,169
- Damn straight.
- But how you look...

390
00:39:08,505 --> 00:39:13,218
I have a head for business and a bod for sin.

391
00:39:13,301 --> 00:39:16,763
Is there anything wrong with that?

392
00:39:16,846 --> 00:39:18,932
No... No.

393
00:39:23,895 --> 00:39:25,814
Hello. Hi.

394
00:39:25,897 --> 00:39:28,149
I have to go now.

395
00:39:28,233 --> 00:39:30,902
- I'll come with you.
- No.

396
00:39:31,611 --> 00:39:33,905
Hey, Tess.

397
00:39:46,084 --> 00:39:48,837
I need some air. Meet me outside. Thank you.

398
00:39:57,220 --> 00:39:58,388
Excuse me.

399
00:40:16,698 --> 00:40:18,199
Hello?

400
00:40:18,283 --> 00:40:20,326
- Hi.
- Hi.

401
00:40:27,750 --> 00:40:30,670
Where do you live?

402
00:40:31,838 --> 00:40:34,466
Where do you live?

403
00:40:34,549 --> 00:40:39,888
Park, trees, tall building.

404
00:40:41,806 --> 00:40:45,226
- 166 Morton. Near Hudson.
- 166 Morton.

405
00:40:58,156 --> 00:41:00,867
Might be kind of a mess.

406
00:41:00,950 --> 00:41:05,872
The cleaning lady
keeps changing days on me.

407
00:41:05,955 --> 00:41:08,124
Anybody's guess.

408
00:41:08,208 --> 00:41:14,130
I'm just warning you cos,
if it's the day before, it could be pretty bad.

409
00:41:19,052 --> 00:41:23,890
I don't notice so much myself,
but some of the people I've had over have,

410
00:41:24,682 --> 00:41:27,602
you know, remarked on it.

411
00:41:39,489 --> 00:41:42,117
It's not so bad.

412
00:42:27,537 --> 00:42:30,331
Would you...

413
00:42:30,415 --> 00:42:33,168
Would you like a nightcap?

414
00:42:35,753 --> 00:42:37,797
I guess not.

415
00:42:39,883 --> 00:42:42,969
I guess it's too late for coffee.

416
00:42:44,804 --> 00:42:48,332
Herb tea? Herb tea...?

417
00:42:49,726 --> 00:42:52,020
I don't have any.

418
00:42:52,103 --> 00:42:56,900
It always sounds good when people
offer it to me when I'm in your shape.

419
00:42:58,318 --> 00:43:01,404
I might have a little brandy myself.

420
00:43:05,408 --> 00:43:08,036
Boy...

421
00:43:08,119 --> 00:43:10,580
You sure are pretty.

422
00:44:46,968 --> 00:44:50,305
Don't fuck up. Don't fuck up.

423
00:44:58,480 --> 00:45:01,357
Hi. Tess McGill to see Jack Trainer.

424
00:45:01,441 --> 00:45:04,360
- May I take your coat?
- Yes, please.

425
00:45:20,210 --> 00:45:22,962
Gentlemen, Tess McGill.

426
00:45:25,632 --> 00:45:28,843
Miss McGill, I'm Jack Trainer.

427
00:45:31,179 --> 00:45:33,431
How are you?

428
00:45:33,515 --> 00:45:35,934
This is John Romano and Bernie Kotar.

429
00:45:36,267 --> 00:45:38,728
Sit down, please.

430
00:45:43,817 --> 00:45:45,735
- Coffee?
- Sure.

431
00:45:45,819 --> 00:45:49,823
- Milk or sugar?
- Both, thank you.

432
00:45:53,034 --> 00:45:55,912
I suppose we should just get right down to it.

433
00:45:55,995 --> 00:45:58,081
Sure.

434
00:46:00,041 --> 00:46:02,585
I've lost my briefcase.

435
00:46:05,004 --> 00:46:09,134
In each of the last three quarters,
Trask Industries has announced plans

436
00:46:09,217 --> 00:46:14,514
to acquire a major market television station,
each time unsuccessfully.

437
00:46:14,597 --> 00:46:18,977
At the same time they've expended time
and money fighting off a hostile takeover attempt

438
00:46:19,102 --> 00:46:22,939
by one of their Japanese competitors.

439
00:46:23,022 --> 00:46:27,569
Buying into radio would, in one fell swoop
accomplish two important tasks.

440
00:46:27,902 --> 00:46:31,072
It would give Trask
a solid base in broadcasting,

441
00:46:31,239 --> 00:46:35,660
and, because of FCC regulations forbidding
foreign ownership of radio stations,

442
00:46:35,743 --> 00:46:39,914
it would wipe out the threat
of a Japanese takeover.

443
00:46:43,251 --> 00:46:45,920
Interesting idea.

444
00:46:46,838 --> 00:46:49,090
But I don't like it.

445
00:46:49,174 --> 00:46:52,218
Trask has got a lot of cash
on their balance sheet.

446
00:46:52,302 --> 00:46:57,682
That's why they're a takeover target.
A radio station is small potatoes.

447
00:46:57,807 --> 00:47:00,143
I can't see him biting.

448
00:47:00,226 --> 00:47:02,854
I've already thought of that.

449
00:47:02,937 --> 00:47:07,525
I figure that we look for a radio network -
one with a real high profile.

450
00:47:07,609 --> 00:47:13,281
And with the surplus cash,
we implement a major stock repurchase.

451
00:47:13,364 --> 00:47:18,161
So Trask is protected and their stock goes up,
and everybody's happy.

452
00:47:24,250 --> 00:47:26,127
Or not.

453
00:47:26,920 --> 00:47:29,672
Shoot me. Just shoot me.

454
00:47:29,756 --> 00:47:33,676
Would you cut that out?
They didn't throw you out, did they?

455
00:47:33,760 --> 00:47:40,642
Well, they don't exactly have bouncers.
They're a little more subtle than that, Cyn.

456
00:47:40,725 --> 00:47:43,645
Oh, God. And last night.

457
00:47:43,895 --> 00:47:48,066
Yeah. I should've checked the milligrams.
Live and learn.

458
00:47:49,317 --> 00:47:54,030
Maybe he'll feel sorry for you, and make it
up to you doing your deal or whatever it is.

459
00:47:54,114 --> 00:47:59,577
I'm not looking for sympathy.
You know, I had a shot at...

460
00:48:02,455 --> 00:48:04,499
It's him. He's here.

461
00:48:04,582 --> 00:48:08,378
Do me a favour. Be me. Be my secretary.

462
00:48:09,003 --> 00:48:11,422
- Tess.
- Cyn, please, do it for me.

463
00:48:11,506 --> 00:48:13,591
OK...

464
00:48:14,551 --> 00:48:15,593
Tess.

465
00:48:24,352 --> 00:48:27,647
- May I help you?
- Jack Trainer to see Miss McGill.

466
00:48:31,443 --> 00:48:34,529
Let's give her a shout, shall we?

467
00:48:36,239 --> 00:48:38,992
